  "2": {
    "John Trapp": "Upon the first day ] The Christian sabbath, the Lord\u2019s day, as the Greek scholiast well renders it; which to sanctify was in the primitive times a badge of Christianity. When the question was propounded, Servasti Dominicum? Hast thou kept the Lord\u2019s day? The answer was returned, Christianus sum; intermittere non possum, I am a Christian, I can do no less than keep the Lord\u2019s day. But the world is now grown perfectly profane (saith Dr King, on Jonah, Lect. 7), and can play on the Lord\u2019s day without book; the sabbath of the Lord, the sanctified day of his rest, is shamelessly troubled and disquieted. Lay by him in store ] Gr. as a treasure, #1Ti 6:18 . Manus pauperum gazophylacium Christi, The poor man\u2019s box is Christ\u2019s treasury. As God hath prospered him ] Gr. \u03b5\u03c5\u03bf\u03b4\u03c9\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 , Given him a good arrival at the end of his voyage, and enabled him; for we may not stretch beyond the staple, and so spoil all.\nVer.\n2. Upon the first day] The Christian sabbath, the Lord\u2019s day, as the Greek scholiast well renders it; which to sanctify was in the primitive times a badge of Christianity. When the question was propounded, Servasti Dominicum? Hast thou kept the Lord\u2019s day? The answer was returned, Christianus sum; intermittere non possum, I am a Christian, I can do no less than keep the Lord\u2019s day. But the world is now grown perfectly profane (saith Dr King, on Jonah, Lect. 7), and can play on the Lord\u2019s day without book; the sabbath of the Lord, the sanctified day of his rest, is shamelessly troubled and disquieted. Lay by him in store] Gr. as a treasure, #1Ti 6:"
  },
